AWS IAM ‚Äì Notes
1Ô∏è‚É£ IAM

AWS IAM is a service used to manage users, access, and permissions in AWS.
It helps control who can access which AWS resources and what actions they can perform.

2Ô∏è‚É£ IAM Users

An IAM user represents a person or application that needs access to AWS.
Each user can have unique credentials like username, password, and access keys.

3Ô∏è‚É£ IAM Groups

IAM groups are collections of users with similar permissions.
Permissions are assigned to the group instead of individual users.

4Ô∏è‚É£ IAM Roles

IAM roles provide temporary access to AWS resources.
They are commonly used by EC2, Lambda, and cross-account access.

5Ô∏è‚É£ IAM Policies

IAM policies are JSON documents that define permissions.
They specify what actions are allowed or denied on which resources.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Permissions

Permissions define what a user or role can do in AWS.
They follow the principle of least privilege.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Authentication vs Authorization

Authentication verifies who you are.
Authorization decides what you are allowed to do.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Access Keys

Access keys are used for programmatic access to AWS.
They consist of an Access Key ID and a Secret Access Key.

9Ô∏è‚É£ MFA (Multi-Factor Authentication)

MFA adds an extra layer of security.
It requires a second verification step along with the password.

üîü IAM Security Best Practices

Avoid using the root account for daily tasks.
Use IAM roles, enable MFA, and apply least-privilege policies.
